Commit Message: Make aaargh a proper Python distribution
A few README.rst additions and fixes
Use correct variable name in example
List Python 3 support in classifier list in setup.py

Add global arguments to subcommands as well

This allows global args to be specified after the subcommand
instead of before, so it avoids forcing ugly invocations such
as "myapp --global-arg=foo start --local-arg".

Do not import module with deps from setup.py

The setup.py script imported the aaargh module, which in turn imported
argparse. This does not work with Python versions older than 2.7, since
argparse is not in the standard library for those versions. Avoid this
problem by copying the version string in setup.py.

Fixes issue #1.
Add a Bitdeli badge to README

No longer add global args to subcommands

This should fix issue #3 and issue #5.

Add LICENSE.rst with 3-clause BSD license text

Resolves issue #9.
No longer use pbr for packaging (issue #12)

Drop argparse from install_requires

Don't add unnecessary external dependency on argparse, since it is in
the stdlib for Python 2.7+. For 2.6 it's an external download, but there
is no reason to default to using an external version while the stdlib
version is just fine.

Fix calling the program without a subcommand under Python 3

Under Python 2, the parse_args() call exits the program if no subcommand
was specified, but under Python 3 this call succeeds, resulting in a
missing '_func' key in the returned dict. Fix that by handling that case
ourselves.

Add alias support to subcommands

Based on David Fraser's work, refs #4.
Cleanup alias code; add some simple tests
Add Travis CI image to README
